A Multi-user, multitasking operating system such as Linux is suitable for this environment.
Multiple users can access the system simultaneously from different terminals or network sessions.
Multitasking allows several programs to run concurrently, enabling many students to execute their programs at the same time.
Resource sharing is efficient because the CPU, memory, storage, and other system resources are managed and allocated among users and processes.
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>

int main() {
    pid_t pid;

    pid = fork();  

    if (pid < 0) {
        printf("Process creation failed\n");
    }
    else if (pid == 0) {
        printf("Child Process ID: %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Parent Process ID from Child: %d\n", getppid());
    }
    else {
        printf("Parent Process ID: %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Child Process ID from Parent: %d\n", pid);
    }
    return 0;
}
output:
Parent Process ID: 2345
Child Process ID from Parent: 2346
Child Process ID: 2346
Parent Process ID from Child: 2345

